name: Launch Procedures
description: Preparation, integration, and launch procedures for the 2025 USLI season.

steps.name: Remove tape on drogue parachute, shroud lines, and shock cord.

content.text: Restricting the parachute, shroud lines, and shock cord can result in the vehicle falling without any method to slow down, leading to a failed recovery.

steps.name: Verify the parachute, shroud lines, and shock cord are free of damage.

content.text: Damage constitutes tears, rips, stiffened areas, burns, or singes.

steps.name: Untangle parachute shroud lines

content.text: Improper storage of the drogue parachute shroud lines can result in the parachute failing to open fully after deployment. This could produce unexpectedly high descent velocities and lead to a failed recovery.

steps.name: Z-fold the parachute

content.text: Improper folding can result in the parachute failing to eject or open fully after deployment. This could produce unexpectedly high descent velocities and lead to a failed recovery.

steps.name: Wrap parachute with the small square of nomex

content.text: If Nomex does not fully cover the parachute, black powder combustion may burn holes in the parachute. This could produce unexpectedly high descent velocities and lead to a failed recovery

steps.name: Wrap the parachute in a rubber band to maintain shape.
Connect the parachute swivel to the nomex with a quick link.

content.text: If Nomex is not attached at the base of the shroud lines, it may lift up along the shroud lines and reef the parachute resulting in high descent velocities and a failed recovery.

steps.name: Verify that the drogue shock cord has a loop for parachute attachment.

content.text: The parachute should be connected roughly 2/3 along the shock cord from the forward end.

tokens.value: The parachute should be connected roughly 2/3 along the shock cord from the forward end.

content.text: Improperly attached quick link may result in the drogue parachute separating from the launch vehicle and cause failed recovery

steps.name: Form bundles of shock cord every 12" along the length of the shock cord using masking tape.

content.text: Ensure that the bundles are not too tight or sparse.
Ensure that the bundles are not too tight or sparse. Bundles that are too tight will inhibit shock cord from fully expanding; bundles that are too sparse will not be effective in absorbing force

tokens.value: Ensure that the bundles are not too tight or sparse. Bundles that are too tight will inhibit shock cord from fully expanding; bundles that are too sparse will not be effective in absorbing force

steps.name: Attach the drogue parachute to the shock cord.

content.text: This connection and others on the harness will be re-verified before flight.

steps.name: Attach a quick link to the forward end of the shock cord.
Attach a quick link to the aft end of the shock cord.
Set aside the completed parachute and recovery harness.
Remove tape on main parachute, shroud lines, and shock cord.

content.text: Restricting the main parachute, shroud lines, and shock cord can result in the vehicle falling without any method to slow down, leading to a failed recovery.

content.text: Improper folding can result in the parachute failing to eject or open fully after deployment. This could produce unexpectedly high descent velocities and lead to a failed recovery.

steps.name: Wrap parachute with the large square of nomex.

content.text: If Nomex does not fully cover the parachute, black powder combustion may burn holes in the parachute. This could produce unexpectedly high descent velocities and lead to a failed recovery

steps.name: Wrap the parachute in a rubber band to maintain shape.
Connect the parachute swivel to the nomex with a quick link.

content.text: If Nomex is not attached at the base of the shroud lines, it may lift up along the shroud lines and reef the parachute resulting in high descent velocities and a failed recovery.

steps.name: Verify that the main shock cord has a loop for parachute attachment.

content.text: Improperly attached quick link may result in the drogue parachute separating from the launch vehicle and cause failed recovery

steps.name: The following steps shall be done by the team mentor.

content.text: Steps involving black powder explosives shall be conducted by the team mentor. All team members should wear safety glasses when black powder explosives are present.

tokens.value: Steps involving black powder explosives shall be conducted by the team mentor. All team members should wear safety glasses when black powder explosives are present.

steps.name: Construct a 5g charge and label it "MAIN -- PRIMARY"
Construct a 6.25g charge and label it "MAIN -- BACKUP"
Construct a 2.5g charge and label it "DROGUE -- PRIMARY"
Construct a 3.5g charge and label it "DROGUE -- BACKUP"
Place all charges in antistatic bag.

content.text: Proper storage of the black powder charges minimizes the risk of static charge buildup.

tokens.value: Proper storage of the black powder charges minimizes the risk of static charge buildup.

steps.name: Connect the primary battery to the primary computer.

content.text: These steps will be repeated on L-0 during vehicle integration.

tokens.value: These steps will be repeated on L-0 during vehicle integration.

steps.name: Connect the backup battery to the backup computer.
Connect the aft bulkhead e-match passthroughs to their labeled mates.
Insert the avionics sled subassembly into the avionics coupler.
Rotate sled until RBF flight tag holes are aligned. Both computers should be disarmed.
Connect the forward bulkhead e-match passthroughs to their labeled mates.
Secure the forward bulkhead with 2x 1/4-20 nuts and washers.
Connect jumper wires to 4x e-match passthroughs on the avionics stack.
Place the avionics stack in a vertical flight-like configuration.
Power on the backup computer.
Verify 3x beeps to indicate nominal continuity.
Power off the backup computer.
Power on the primary computer.
Verify 3x beeps to indicate nominal continuity.
Verify signal acquisition by TeleBT ground station.
Power off primary computer.
Remove 4x jumper wires.
Inspect fins and verify that they are undamaged and free of cracks.

content.text: In the event that a fin is damaged, replace the damaged fin with a spare.
This step and the following are the final check-off for flight readiness. Failure to inspect any element of the vehicle prior to flight may result in catastrophic failure during flight or recovery.

tokens.value: This step and the following are the final check-off for flight readiness. Failure to inspect any element of the vehicle prior to flight may result in catastrophic failure during flight or recovery.

steps.name: Slide each fin axially until the locator pins are in place.
Install the thrust plate on top of the fins so that the 2 pins on each fin slide into place.
Attach the thrust plate to the aft airframe using 1/4-20 x 0.5'' bolts.
Verify the motor mount tube is secured in place.
Verify that the fins cannot move radially or axially.
Verify that the bolts holding the fin clamps in place are fully tightened .
Verify that the rail buttons are fully tightened.
Verify that the following are free of cracks and unintended holes.

content.text:

- Couplers
- Bulkheads

- Bulkheads

content.text: Once the battery is connected, the STEMCRaFT will be powered on until payload preparation is complete.

tokens.value: Once the battery is connected, the STEMCRaFT will be powered on until payload preparation is complete.

steps.name: Preform the IMU calibration sequence until the buzzer indicates that calibration is STORED and complete.

content.text:
1. Pick up the PCB and wave it around and turn it in a circular motion for 5-7 seconds

2. Place the IMU on a flat surface making the direction on top 'up'
     - Leave for 5 seconds
     - Make sure the left side of the PCB stays on the table and tilt the right side is lifted 45 degrees (rocking the boat)
     - Leave for 5 seconds
     - Make sure the right side of the PCB stays on the table and tilt the left side is lifted 45 degrees (rocking the boat)
     - Leave for 5 seconds
     - Make sure the back side (side closest to you) of the PCB stays on the table and tilt the front side (furthest away) is lifted 45 degrees (rocking the boat)
     - Leave for 5 seconds

3. Now flip the PCB upside down and start the tilting procedure again (rocking the Australian boat)
     - Leave for 5 seconds
     - Make sure the left side of the PCB stays on the table and tilt the right side is lifted 45 degrees (rocking the boat)
     - Leave for 5 seconds
     - Make sure the right side of the PCB stays on the table and tilt the left side is lifted 45 degrees (rocking the boat)
     - Leave for 5 seconds
     - Make sure the back side (side closest to you) of the PCB stays on the table and tilt the front side (furthest away) is lifted 45 degrees (rocking the boat)
     - Leave for 5 seconds

4. Flip the PCB again so that the IMU is in the 'up' position and leave on a flat surface for 5 seconds

steps.name: When commanded, turn off radio transmission from the STEMCRaFT using the LoRa base station.
Locate the vehicle using visual cues or the GPS locator.
Check surroundings around vehicle to ensure no part has landed in a hazardous environment.

content.text: Hazardous environments include power lines, trees, or water.

steps.name: Take photos of each section of the vehicle.
Wait 3:00 minutes before making contact with vehicle.
Disarm both altimeters.
Access any encloses charge locations and verify detonation of all charges.
Record observed damage to the vehicle and recovery system.
Disconnect the primary and drogue recovery harnesses.
Disconnect and bundle the primary and drogue parachutes.
Transport all sections of the vehicle back to base.
Disconnect all vehicle sections and recovery harness hardware.
Clean the inside of the vehicle airframes using isopropyl alcohol.
Disassemble the avionics bay and remove ungrounded electrical connections.
Clean the avionics bay bulkheads using isopropyl alcohol.
Clean the outside of the vehicle with a damp cloth.

content.text: Isopropyl alcohol will degrade paint if present on the vehicle.

Wait for all launch vehicles remaining on the pad to launch or cycle.
With RSO approval, approach the vehicle.
Remove the igniter.
Power off the primary and backup computers.

tokens.value: Explosives present. Power off computers before further moving or adjusting the vehicle to prevent premature ejection charge detonation.

steps.name: Remove launch vehicle from launch pad and return to the work area.
Remove motor and soak it in water to minimize ignition risk.
